t and Health -- tCase Study: The Environment and Health -- t12. Education and Information -- tCase Study: Education, Economic Disadvantage, and Homeless Students in Pennsylvania’s Marcellus Shale Gas Region -- t13. Crime, Punishment, and Spatial Inequality -- tCase Study: Violence Against Women in America’s Heartland -- tPART V. Programs, Policy, and Politics -- t14. The Safety Net in Rural America -- t15. The Opportunities and Limits of Economic Growth -- t16. Politics and Policy: Barriers and Opportunities for Rural Peoples -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerica's rural areas have always held a disproportionate share of the nation's poorest populations. Rural Poverty in the United States examines why. What is it about the geography, demography, and history of rural communities that keeps them poor? In a comprehensive analysis that extends from the Civil War to the present, Rural Poverty in the United States looks at access to human and social capital; food security; healthcare and the environment; homelessness; gender roles and relations; racial inequalities; and immigration trends to isolate the underlying causes of persistent rural poverty.Contributors to this volume incorporate approaches from multiple disciplines, including sociology, economics, demography, race and gender studies, public health, education, criminal justice, social welfare, and other social science fields. They take a hard look at current and past programs to alleviate rural poverty and use their failures to suggest alternatives that could improve the well-being of rural Americans for years to come. These essays work hard to define rural poverty's specific metrics and markers, a critical step for building better policy and practice. Considering gender, race, and immigration, the book appreciates the overlooked structural and institutional dimensions of ongoing rural poverty and its larger social consequences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPovertyzUnited States. 0aRural poorzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh1 aAbel, Richard D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiddle, Catharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandler, Raeven Faye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman-Jensen, Alisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeKeseredy, Walter S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEason, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEly, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngle, Elyzabeth W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Gary Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenberg, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall-Sanchez, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Rosalind P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Jill Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Mark H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendryx, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensen, Leif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Kenneth M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLay, J. Celeste, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMette, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Kathleen, econtributor.